31","1273":"1273","Wiltshire, England":"Wiltshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Cherhill, Wiltshire, England":"Cherhill, Wiltshire, England","North, Wiltshire, England":"Wiltshire, England"},"en":{"1215–1273":"1215–1273","1210–1238":"1210–1238","1231–1273":"1231–1273","1238":"1238","1215":"1215","1259":"1259","1224":"1224","28 Jan 1238":"28 January 1238","1210":"1210","1231":"1231","1273":"1273","Wiltshire, England":"Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom","Cherhill, Wiltshire, England":"Cherhill, Wiltshire, England","North, Wiltshire, England":"Wiltshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Goddard","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): from <i>Godhard</i>, a personal name composed of the ancient Germanic elements <i>gōd</i> ‘good’ or <i>god</i>, <i>got</i> ‘god’ + <i>hard</i> ‘hardy, brave, strong’. The name was popular in Europe during the Middle Ages as a result of the fame of Saint Gotthard, an 11th-century bishop of Hildesheim who founded a hospice on the pass from Switzerland to Italy that bears his name. This surname is also borne by Ashkenazic Jews, presumably as an Americanized form of one or more similar (like-sounding) Jewish surnames.","English: perhaps occasionally a variant of the occupational name   Gothard  . The two surnames may have been much confused.","French: variant of   Godard  , a cognate of 1 above."],"variants":[{"name":"Gothard","meanings":["English: variant of   Goddard  .","English: occupational name for a keeper of goats, from Middle English <i>gotherde</i> (Old English <i>gāt</i> ‘goat’ + <i>hierde</i>) ‘herdsman, keeper’.","English: variant of <b>Goater</b>, with excrescent <i>-d</i>, either a topographic name for someone who lived by a stream or ditch, from Middle English <i>gote</i> ‘watercourse’ + the agent suffix <i>-(e)r</i>, or an occupational name either from Middle English <i>gotherde</i> ‘goatherd’ or from Middle English <i>goter</i> ‘goatherd’, an agent derivative of Middle English <i>got(e)</i> ‘goat’ (Old English <i>gāt</i>)."]},{"name":"Godard","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Pierre, Reynald, Alcide, Armand, Aurel, Celine, Cyprien, Dominique, Emile, Etienne, Euclide, Gilles.","French: from the personal name <i>Godard</i>, of ancient Germanic origin (see   Goddard  ).","English (of Norman origin): variant of   Goddard  , a cognate of 1 above. This surname is also borne by Ashkenazic Jews, presumably as an Americanized form of one or more similar (like-sounding) Jewish surnames."]},{"name":"Goertz","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Alois, Christoph, Erwin, Guenter, Juergen, Kurt, Otto.","German (also <b>Görtz</b>): patronymic from the personal name <i>Goert</i>, a short form of <i>Godhard</i> (see   Goddard  ),   Gottfried   or   Gerhardt  , common in Rhineland.","Germanized form (also <b>Görtz</b>) of Sorbian <b>Gerc</b>; see   Gertz  ."]},{"name":"Goodart","meanings":["English: variant of   Goddard  .","Perhaps also an Americanized form of German   Gothard  ."]}]},{"name":"Walter","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French personal name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>wald</i> ‘rule’ + <i>heri</i>, <i>hari</i> ‘army’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, superseding the native Old English form, <i>Wealdhere</i>. It was a very popular name in medieval England, normally pronounced ‘Water’."],"variants":[{"name":"Walther","meanings":["from <i>wald</i> ‘rule’ + <i>heri</i> ‘army’; name of the famous medieval minnesinger  Walther von der Vogelweide  (  <i>c.</i>1170– <i>c.</i>1230 )."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":0,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Ar